and his return was accompanied by murder and plunder. It does not appear, I think, at what time of the year Marius entered Rome; but the events which are related seem to show that it was late. He and

Cinna declared themselves consuls for the year Rc. 86, but Marius died in the month of January of that year (Appian, B C i. 75). The time between his return and his death was a dreadful period of proscription and murder ; audit seems very unlikely that Cicero saw any thing of Marius after his return, unless he heard him make a Contio. During all the time after his return Marius “nihil nisi de inimicis ulciscendis agebat,’' says the writer, and though Cicero might be in no danger from his ‘ municeps‚’ it is probable that he kept out of his way. But we know nothing exact of this period of Cicero’s life.

But what did Marius say after this long and tiresome preface, ‘tum se fuisse mise- ru1n‚’ &c.? He said, “ se non commis- surum . . . quam numquam perdidisset..” It would not be possible to invent any thing less appropriate to the character of this

mad, worn out with disease, who shed blood without mercy, and died in a short time exhausted by his own vengeance and filled with terror at the expected return of his enemy Sulla, as cruel as himself, and young and vigorous (Plut. Marius, c. 45, &c.).-—‘conservaret:’ ‘conservasset,’ Ma- nutius.
